{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b UNDERSTANDING THE STORM}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A panic attack is the Amygdala seizing the bridge.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What happens biologically:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab The Amygdala detects a \u8220"threat\u8221" (real or perceived)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab It triggers the HPA Axis, flooding your body with Adrenaline and Cortisol\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Your Prefrontal Cortex goes offline\u8212-you lose access to rational thinking\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Your body prepares for mortal combat: heart races, breathing shallows, muscles tense\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab With no actual predator to fight or flee, the chemicals have nowhere to go\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab The body interprets its own symptoms as evidence of more danger\u8212-creating a feedback loop\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The cruel irony:} Panic attacks feel like dying, but they are not dangerous. Your body is doing exactly what it evolved to do. The alarm is false, but the alarm system is working correctly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The duration:} A panic attack typically peaks within 10 minutes and subsides within 20-30 minutes. The chemicals will metabolize. The storm will pass. Your job is to survive the next 20 minutes without making things worse.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b IMMEDIATE PROTOCOL: THE MAYDAY DRILL}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When the panic hits, you do not think. You execute.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b STEP 1: STOP}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Freeze. Do not make any decisions. Do not send any messages. Do not drive. You are compromised. The Operator is offline.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Say out loud (or in your head): {\i \u8220"This is a panic response. I am not dying. This will pass.\u8221"}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b STEP 2: GROUND (5-4-3-2-1)}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Panic pulls you into your head. This drill pulls you back into your body.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Look around and name out loud:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b 5 things you can SEE} (\u8220"I see the wall. I see the lamp. I see my hand\u8230 ?\u8221")\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b 4 things you can TOUCH} (\u8220"I feel the chair. I feel my feet on the floor\u8230 ?\u8221")\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b 3 things you can HEAR} (\u8220"I hear the fan. I hear traffic. I hear my breathing\u8230 ?\u8221")\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b 2 things you can SMELL} (\u8220"I smell coffee. I smell nothing particular\u8230 ?\u8221")\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b 1 thing you can TASTE} (\u8220"I taste toothpaste\u8230 ?\u8221")\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Why it works:} This technique, called {\b Sensory Grounding}, forces the brain to engage with the present moment. You cannot be in \u8220"future catastrophe\u8221" mode and \u8220"counting objects\u8221" mode simultaneously. It switches the neural tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b STEP 3: BREATHE (Box Breathing)}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The fastest way to deactivate the panic response is through the Vagus Nerve. The Vagus Nerve runs from your brain to your gut and controls the \u8220"Rest and Digest\u8221" system.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Extended exhale activates the Vagus Nerve.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Execute Box Breathing (see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#chapter-7-radar-calibration"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Chapter 7
}}}
):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Inhale for 4 seconds\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Hold for 4 seconds\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Exhale for 4 seconds\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Hold for 4 seconds\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Repeat 4 cycles\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If 4 seconds is too long, use 3. The ratio matters more than the duration.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Variation: Physiological Sigh}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Neuroscientist Andrew Huberman describes this as the fastest way to calm down:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Inhale through the nose\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab At the top, take a second small inhale (topping off the lungs)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Long slow exhale through the mouth\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 One to three of these can significantly reduce heart rate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b STEP 4: COLD}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If still escalating, apply cold:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Hold ice cubes in your hands\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Splash cold water on your face\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Put a cold pack on the back of your neck\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Why it works:} The cold triggers the {\b Dive Reflex}, which slows heart rate and redirects blood flow. It is a biological override switch.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b STEP 5: MOVE (If Safe)}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are in a safe location, movement helps metabolize the stress chemicals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Walk, even just around the room\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Shake your hands vigorously\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Do jumping jacks\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You are completing the stress cycle that the body started.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b STEP 6: CONTACT}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you have a safe person (see {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#chapter-12-fleet-maneuvers"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Chapter 12
}}}
: Fleet Maneuvers), reach out:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Call or text them\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Say: \u8220"I am having anxiety. I do not need you to fix it. I just need to hear a calm voice.\u8221"\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Co-regulation is real. Another person\u8217's calm nervous system can help calm yours.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b AFTER THE STORM: POST-CRISIS PROTOCOL}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once the immediate crisis passes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b 1. Do Not Shame Yourself}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Passenger will try to make you feel weak for having panic. Ignore it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Panic attacks are not a character flaw. They are a nervous system response. Navy SEALs get panic attacks. Surgeons get panic attacks. CEOs get panic attacks. You are in good company.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b 2. Hydrate and Rest}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your body just ran a marathon internally. Drink water. Eat something light. Rest if you can. The next few hours, treat yourself like someone recovering from a physical ordeal\u8212-because you are.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b 3. Log It}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you are able, open your Field Journal and document:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b MAYDAY LOG \u8212- [Date/Time]}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Trigger (if known):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Duration:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Severity (1-10):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What helped:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What made it worse:\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is data collection. Over time, you will see patterns. Maybe panic hits at the same time of day. Maybe it follows certain triggers. Knowledge is power.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b 4. Review Your Hardware}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Panic attacks often have biological contributors:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sleep:} Have you been getting enough?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Caffeine:} Have you had too much?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Blood sugar:} Have you eaten?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Substances:} Alcohol withdrawal and hangover anxiety are real\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes the most effective \u8220"psychological\u8221" intervention is a sandwich and a nap.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b ANTICIPATORY ANXIETY: THE FEAR OF THE FEAR}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes the worst part is not the panic itself\u8212-it is the fear that panic might come.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This creates avoidance: You stop going places, doing things, living life\u8212-all to avoid triggering another attack.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Operator\u8217's Stance:}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Panic is unpleasant, but it is not dangerous. The thing you fear (the panic attack) is uncomfortable, but it cannot actually harm you.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The goal is not to never have anxiety. The goal is to {\b stop being afraid of feeling anxious.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When anticipatory anxiety arises:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Name it: \u8220"The Passenger is predicting a storm that may never come.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Accept the possibility: \u8220"I might feel anxious. That is okay. I know what to do.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Proceed anyway: \u8220"We are going to the event. The Passenger can be anxious if it wants.\u8221"\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Avoidance strengthens fear. Approach\u8212-even anxious approach\u8212-weakens it.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b WHEN PANIC BECOMES CHRONIC}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you are experiencing:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Panic attacks more than once a week\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Constant background anxiety that does not respond to these techniques\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Avoidance that significantly limits your life\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is above the scope of a field manual. You need professional support\u8212-not because you are weak, but because chronic panic may indicate a nervous system condition that requires specialized treatment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Options include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT):} Evidence-based treatment for anxiety disorders\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b EMDR:} Particularly if trauma is involved\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Medication:} Sometimes necessary to stabilize the system enough for therapy to work\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#appendix-medevac"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Appendix MEDEVAC
}}}
 for guidance on finding help.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b THE PANIC IS A MESSAGE}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here is the reframe that may help:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Panic is the Passenger screaming because it believes you are in danger. The Passenger is not trying to ruin your life\u8212-it is trying to protect you with a broken alarm system.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you respond to panic with compassion rather than frustration, something shifts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Instead of: {\i \u8220"What is wrong with me?\u8221"} Try: {\i \u8220"The Passenger is very scared right now. I hear you. We are safe. Let me show you.\u8221"}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then show it\u8212-through grounding, breathing, and riding out the storm\u8212-that you can handle this. With enough repetitions, the Passenger learns to trust the Operator\u8217's leadership.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The alarms become less frequent. Not because you suppressed them\u8212-because the system no longer believes it needs to sound them.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
